North Korea declares "no chance" of unilateral disarmament without trust
On Saturday, the North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations that further sanctions would increase mistrust in the United States and that there is no way North Korea would unilaterally disarm and give up nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho said in the UN General Assembly that North Korea last year took "significant measures of goodwill", for example, stopped nuclear and missile tests, disarmed a nuclear test station and made a decision to stop the development of nuclear technology and weapons.
"But we did not get a satisfactory reaction from the United States," he added.
"If we don't trust the United States, we don't have faith in our national security either, under such circumstances there's no way we're going to disarm ourselves unilaterally."
Although Ri reiterated the known complaints of North Korea against Washington's resistance to "progressive" denuclearisation within which the sanctions would gradually be lifted in North Korea, his statement was significant because he did not reject unilateral denuclearisation as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first meeting in the history of the current president of the United States and the leader of North Korea in Singapore on June 12th, when Kim promised to work on the "denucularisation of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump guaranteed the security of North Korea.
North Korea wants to officially end a Korean war that lasted from 1950 to 1953, but the United States has conditioned that Pyongyang give up nuclear weapons before that.
Washington has also ignored calls for a reduction in strict international sanctions for North Korea.
"The US insists that a denuclearisation be carried out before that and increase pressure by means of sanctions in order to force its goal, and even oppose the "end of war declaration", Ri added.
"The perception that sanctions can throw us on our knees is only a delusion of people who know nothing about us.
The main problem is that the continuation of sanctions increases mistrust."
Ri didn't mention whether there were plans for a second meeting of Kim and Trump that the president of the United States talked about at the beginning of the week in the United Nations.
But the minister stressed that Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in held three meetings in the last five months and added: "If denuclearisation had been sought by South Korea, not the United States, the denuclearisation of the Korean Peninsula would not have taken place like this."
Whatever the case, the tone of speech of Minister Rie differed greatly from that of last year when he spoke to the UN General Assembly and said that targeting the continental U.S. rockets was inevitable after evil President Trump called Kim "a man's rocket" on a suicidal mission.
Trump, who last year threatened "complete destruction" of North Korea this year in the United Nations, praised Kim for his courage to disarm, but added that they still have a lot of work to do and that sanctions must remain in force until North Korea carries out denuclearisation.
Trump said on Wednesday there is no time frame for denuclearisation and added, "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia have voiced the view that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
