German new warship put on hold again
The German Navy's latest frigate was scheduled to be launched in 2014 to replace old warships from the Cold War era, but will not be ready until at least next year due to faulty systems and cost increases, local media reported.
The release of the ship ‘Rheinland-Pfalz’, the leading ship of the brand new frigates of the Baden-Wuertemberg class, is now delayed until the first half of 2019, reports the Die Zeit newspaper, citing a military spokesman.
The ship was due to join the Navy in 2014, but worrying problems after the delivery struck the fate of an ambitious project.
Four vessels of the Baden-Wuertemberg class, ordered by the navy in 2007, will replace the old Bremen class frigates.
As far as is known, it will have a powerful cannon, a series of anti-aircraft and anti-ship rockets, as well as some invisible technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include the longer maintenance period and should be possible to deploy the latest frigates over a period of up to two years without returning to the port of origin.
However, the constant delays mean that the most modern warships, which are said to allow Germany to show its power abroad, will already become obsolete by the time we enter the service, notes Die Zeit.
The unfortunate frigate F125 arrived at all the headlines last year, when the German Navy officially refused to release the ship into service and returned it to Blohm & Voss Shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the Navy has returned the ship to the ship builder after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons for the return, but the German media cited a number of key "software and hardware deficiencies" that would make a warship useless if it were sent on a combat mission.
Software shortages were particularly important because ships of the Baden-Wuertemberg class will be managed by crews of about 120 sailors, half as much as on the older Bremen class frigates.
It has also proved that the ship is dramatically too heavy to reduce its efficiency and restricts the Navy's ability to add future upgrades.
It is believed that the “Rheinland-Pfalz” of 7,000 tonnes is twice the size of ships similar to those used by Germans in World War II.
In addition to faulty hardware, the cost of the entire project will also become a problem, including crew training.
It is said that the price has reached an amazing 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion dollars) compared to the initial 2.2 billion euros.
Problems affecting the latest frigates have become particularly important in light of recent warnings that the German naval force is reducing.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German Defence Committee, admitted that the navy is in fact " running out of ships capable of deploying".
The official said the problem has increased over time, as the old ships were put out of operation and there were no replacement vessels.
He expressed regret that none of the frigates of the Baden-Würtemberg class could join the Navy.
The National Foundation is listening to the secret life of bats
New research carried out on a property in Scotland is aimed at finding out how bats use landscapes to hunt food.
There is hope that the results will clarify the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help to manage future conservation activities.
The study conducted by scientists at the National Foundation for Scotland (NTS) will be followed by ordinary and swamped dwarf bats, as well as brown long-winded and river bats in Inverewa gardens in Wester Ross.
Special cameramen will be placed in key places around the property to monitor bat activities throughout the season.
The NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile examinations using hand detectors.
The professional analysis of the sound of all the recordings will determine the frequency of bat voting and what kind of noise it does.
Then a map of habitats and a report will be drawn to create a detailed picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, a consultant for the protection of the nature of the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal what areas of habitat are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of work on habitat management, such as the creation of meadows and how best to maintain forest surfaces for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom decreased significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and work on the arrangement that affects shelters and the loss of habitats.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a danger, as well as flies and certain chemical treatments of building material, and attacks of pet cats.
The bats aren't actually blind.
However, because of their night hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation technique to find bugs and obstacles on the path of their flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout the country, takes bats very seriously.
There are ten trained experts who regularly conduct research, shelter inspections, and sometimes rescue.
The organisation even set up the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at the estate of Threave in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of the ten bat species living in Scotland live.
The manager, David Thompson, says the estate is an ideal area for them.
"Here in Threave we have huge bat space," he said.
"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitats.
However, there is much more that we do not know about bats, so the work we do here and on other objects will help us to understand better what they need for progress."
It stresses the importance of checking the presence of bats before starting maintenance work inside buildings, since the accidental destruction of one litter can kill up to 400 females and young people, possibly destroying the entire local population.
Bats are protected and illegal to kill, torture or harass or destroy their shelters.
Elisabeth Ferrell, representative of the Scottish Bat Protection Association, encouraged the public to help.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we simply don't know how their population is progressing."
